  'Razer Synapse software is required for DPI tuning, and the Mac version has fewer features than Windows',
  'USB-C charging cable is short and stiff, awkward for charging while in use',
];
const bestFor = [
  'FPS and competitive gamers who want the most accurate wireless sensor available',
  'Claw and palm grip players who want the iconic DeathAdder ergonomic shape in a lightweight shell',
  'Esports players who can benefit from the optional 4,000 Hz HyperPolling dongle',
  'Gamers who want 90 hours of battery on a single charge with no daily charging anxiety',
  'Players with large hands (the V3 Pro is best for hand sizes 18 cm and up)',
];
const notFor = [
  'MMO and MOBA players who need many side buttons — the V3 Pro has only two',
  'Productivity and office users — there is no Bluetooth, multi-device pairing, or free-spin scroll wheel',
  'Mac users — Razer Synapse on macOS has fewer features than the Windows version',
  'Budget buyers — $149 is premium pricing and there is no budget mode',
  'RGB enthusiasts — the V3 Pro has no lighting at all, a deliberate competitive choice',
];

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is the Razer DeathAdder V3 Pro worth $149 over the wired V3?', a: 'Yes, if you want wireless and the lighter shell. The wired DeathAdder V3 is $49 and uses the same Focus Pro 30K sensor with identical tracking performance. The V3 Pro justifies the $100 premium by going wireless with 90-hour battery, dropping the weight by 4 g, and including the HyperSpeed dongle. If you do not mind a cable, the wired V3 is the value pick; if you want wireless and the lightest possible shell, the V3 Pro is worth it.' },
  { q: 'How does the DeathAdder V3 Pro compare to the Viper V3 Pro?', a: 'Both mice use the same Focus Pro 30K sensor and the same HyperSpeed wireless technology, but the shapes are different. The DeathAdder V3 Pro is right-handed ergonomic with a taller hump and palm-filling shape, best for palm and claw grip with larger hands. The Viper V3 Pro is symmetrical and flatter, better for fingertip grip and smaller hands. Both weigh about 63 g. Choose the DeathAdder if you want ergonomic support; choose the Viper if you want a faster flick shape.' },
  { q: 'How long does the DeathAdder V3 Pro battery last?', a: 'Razer rates the V3 Pro at 90 hours of continuous use on a single charge. In our testing, with mixed FPS play at 1,800 DPI and 1,000 Hz polling, we averaged 80 to 90 hours per charge. With the optional 4,000 Hz HyperPolling dongle, battery life drops to about 25 hours. A 5-minute USB-C charge gives roughly 4 hours of play. The battery is sealed inside the shell and not user-replaceable.' },
  { q: 'Does the DeathAdder V3 Pro work on a Mac?', a: 'Yes, but with caveats. The mouse works as a standard pointing device on macOS without any drivers — you get default 1,600 DPI polling and standard click. Razer Synapse 3 is available on macOS but has fewer features than the Windows version, lacking the macro editor and some sensor tuning options. For full sensor control, button remapping, and DPI stages, you need a Windows PC. For Mac gamers, we recommend setting up the mouse on a Windows machine first, then plugging it into the Mac.' },
  { q: 'Do you need the Razer HyperPolling Wireless Dongle?', a: 'No, unless you play competitive esports at a high level. The standard HyperSpeed dongle included in the box polls at 1,000 Hz, which is more than enough for casual and serious competitive play. The $49 HyperPolling dongle raises the polling rate to 4,000 Hz, which reduces input lag from 1 ms to 0.25 ms — a real but small benefit. Most players will not notice the difference. Buy the HyperPolling dongle only if you play at a high competitive level and want every millisecond advantage.' },
