          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of FPS and competitive play across Valorant, CS2, and Apex Legends</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Razer DeathAdder V3 Pro</strong> is the best wireless gaming mouse for right-handed FPS players in 2026. The Focus Pro 30K sensor is the most accurate we have tested, the 63g shell is light without holes, and the 90-hour battery removes daily charging anxiety. At $149 it is expensive, has no RGB and only two side buttons, and the Mac software is weaker — but if you want the most accurate wireless mouse for competitive play, this is the one.
      </div>

      <p>The DeathAdder is Razer's longest-running gaming mouse line, and the V3 Pro — released in 2022 and still a top seller in 2026 — is the wireless flagship. We bought one at retail and put it through 60 days of daily FPS play across Valorant, CS2, and Apex Legends, plus office work and macOS testing, to see whether $149 is justified when the wired V3 is $49.</p>

      <p>This review focuses on the V3 Pro specifically. For productivity-focused alternatives with Bluetooth and multi-device pairing, see our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">best wireless mouse for productivity</a> roundup, and the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">Logitech MX Master 3S review</a> for the productivity counterpart.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this mouse is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Focus Pro 30K Sensor: The Most Accurate We Have Tested</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of the DeathAdder V3 Pro is the Focus Pro 30K optical sensor, Razer's flagship sensor co-developed with PixArt. It tracks up to 30,000 DPI (resolution), 750 IPS (maximum speed), and 70 G acceleration — well beyond the reach of any human wrist motion. In our 60 days of testing, we never observed tracking errors, spin-outs, or sensor rattle on any surface, including cloth pads, hard pads, and a bare desk.</p>

      <p>The sensor also handles lift-off cleanly. The V3 Pro features Razer's Smart Tracking, which calibrates the lift-off distance automatically to your pad surface — we measured 1 mm on a cloth pad and 0.7 mm on a hard pad. There is no manual tuning needed. The sensor also supports asymmetric cut-off, where you can set a low lift-off distance and a high landing distance — useful for low-sensitivity players who lift the mouse frequently.</p>

      <p>The default DPI stages are 400, 800, 1,600, 3,200, and 6,400, adjustable in 1 DPI increments in Razer Synapse. We settled on 1,600 DPI at 1,000 Hz polling for most FPS play, and 800 DPI at 1,000 Hz for low-sensitivity Valorant sessions. The DPI cycle button is on the underside, which prevents accidental presses mid-game.</p>

      <h3>Weight and Shell: 63g Without Holes</h3>
      <p>The V3 Pro weighs 63 g — a dramatic drop from the 88 g DeathAdder V2 Pro. The shell is solid, with no holes in the top or bottom plate, which sets it apart from competitor ultralights like the Glorious Model O which use honeycomb shells. The result is a mouse that feels premium, does not collect dust and sweat in the holes, and still weighs less than most wireless gaming mice.</p>

      <p>The shell material is a slightly textured plastic that grips well without being sticky. The side grips are textured rubber inserts that provide secure claw grip. The buttons are Razer's optical Gen-3 switches, rated for 90 million clicks — they have a crisp, light feel with no pre-travel, and we did not experience any double-click issues during testing. The scroll wheel is tactile with defined notches and a slightly firmer middle-click than the V2 Pro.</p>

      <p>The shape is the iconic DeathAdder ergonomic right-handed design, with a flared right side that supports the ring and pinky fingers, and a thumb rest on the left. The hump is medium-tall and positioned toward the back, which fills the palm for palm grip users. Claw grip players will find the hump pushes the hand slightly forward — a matter of preference. The shape is best for hand sizes 18 cm and up; smaller hands will prefer the Viper V3 Pro.</p>

      <h3>Wireless and Battery: 90 Hours at 1,000 Hz</h3>
      <p>The V3 Pro uses Razer's HyperSpeed wireless dongle, which is a 2.4 GHz radio optimized for low latency. In our tests, input lag measured 1 ms at 1,000 Hz polling — indistinguishable from a wired mouse. We played Valorant and CS2 for 60 days and never noticed any wireless dropouts, stuttering, or interference, even with a Wi-Fi 6E router and a Bluetooth headset nearby.</p>

      <p>Battery life is the headline feature for daily use. Razer rates the V3 Pro at 90 hours at 1,000 Hz polling, and in our mixed-use testing (FPS play at 1,800 DPI, plus some office work), we averaged 80 to 90 hours per charge. With the optional $49 HyperPolling dongle at 4,000 Hz polling, battery life drops to about 25 hours — the trade-off for the four-times-higher polling rate.</p>

      <p>Charging is over USB-C. A 5-minute charge gives roughly 4 hours of play. A full charge from empty takes about 90 minutes. The included USB-C cable is braided and 1.8 m long, but it is stiff and awkward for charging while in use — we recommend a separate flexible USB-C cable if you want to play while charging. The battery is sealed inside the shell and not user-replaceable, which is a long-term concern given that lithium-ion cells degrade over time.</p>

      <h3>Switches, Feet, and Build Quality</h3>
      <p>The V3 Pro uses Razer's optical Gen-3 mouse switches, which use a light beam to register clicks instead of physical contact. The benefit is no debounce delay and no double-click degradation — we measured click latency at 0.2 ms. The downside is a slightly firmer, more tactile click feel that some users find less satisfying than mechanical switches. The switches are rated for 90 million clicks, twice the industry standard.</p>

      <p>The mouse feet are 100% PTFE, with no filler material. The result is a smooth glide across cloth and hard pads with no break-in period. We tested the V3 Pro on a Logitech G640 cloth pad and an Artisan Shidenkai hard pad, and the glide was consistent and fast on both. The feet are 0.6 mm thick, which is on the thinner side — serious competitors may want to swap to aftermarket Tiger Ice feet for a slightly faster glide.</p>

      <p>Build quality is excellent. The shell has no flex when squeezed, the buttons have no rattle, and the scroll wheel has minimal side-to-side wobble. The mouse weighs 63 g without feeling fragile — Razer has done impressive engineering to keep the shell rigid at this weight. The only build concern is the sealed battery, which is a long-term sustainability issue if you keep a mouse for 3+ years.</p>

      <h3>Razer Synapse and the HyperPolling Dongle</h3>
      <p>Razer Synapse 3 is required for DPI tuning, button remapping, polling rate adjustment, and firmware updates. The software is free on Windows and macOS, but the Mac version has fewer features — it lacks the macro editor and some sensor tuning options. For Mac gamers, we recommend setting up the mouse on a Windows PC first, then plugging it into the Mac.</p>

      <p>The HyperPolling Wireless Dongle is a separate $49 accessory that raises the polling rate from 1,000 Hz to 4,000 Hz. The benefit is reduced input lag — from 1 ms to 0.25 ms — which is real but small. Most players will not notice the difference. The HyperPolling dongle is worth buying only if you play competitive esports at a high level and want every possible advantage. For everyone else, the included HyperSpeed dongle is more than sufficient.</p>

      <p>Synapse also includes a Hypershift mode that lets you bind a secondary function set to a button (typically the DPI button underneath), doubling the available buttons. We did not find Hypershift useful in FPS play, but it is a nice option for productivity users who want to remap the side buttons.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The V3 Pro competes against the Razer Viper V3 Pro, the Logitech G Pro X Superlight 2, the SteelSeries Prime Wireless, and the wired DeathAdder V3. Here is how they stack up:</p>

