        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Razer Viper V3 Pro</strong> is the natural alternative within Razer's lineup. It uses the same Focus Pro 30K sensor and HyperSpeed wireless, with identical 63 g weight and 90-hour battery. The difference is the shape — the Viper is symmetric and flatter, better for fingertip grip and smaller hands. The DeathAdder is better for palm and claw grip with larger hands. Choose based on grip style.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Logitech G Pro X Superlight 2</strong> is the cross-brand rival at $159. It is 3 g lighter, has marginally longer battery, and uses Logitech's HERO 2 sensor with 32,000 DPI. The shape is symmetric and slightly smaller than the DeathAdder. The two mice are very close in performance — choose the one that fits your hand and grip style.</p>

      <p>The <strong>SteelSeries Prime Wireless</strong> is the value pick at $99. It is 9 g heavier, has a slightly weaker sensor (26,000 DPI, 500 IPS), and only 40 hours of battery — but it is $50 cheaper and still excellent for most competitive play. See our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">wireless mouse roundup</a> for the budget breakdown.</p>

      <p>The wired <strong>Razer DeathAdder V3</strong> is the value champion at $49. It uses the same Focus Pro 30K sensor with identical tracking performance, weighs 4 g less, and saves $100. The only reasons to pay the premium for the V3 Pro are wireless and battery life. If you do not mind a cable, the wired V3 is the best deal in the lineup.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the V3 Pro at full price if you want the most accurate wireless gaming mouse for right-handed FPS play. The Focus Pro 30K sensor, 63 g shell, and 90-hour battery are best-in-class, and the iconic DeathAdder shape is unmatched for palm and claw grip.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Razer runs frequent promotions on the V3 Pro during Prime Day, Black Friday, and back-to-school events, and we have seen it drop to $99 to $119 during those windows. A $30 to $50 discount is common and worth waiting a few weeks for if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the V3 Pro and buy the wired DeathAdder V3 if you want the same sensor and shape for $49. The wired V3 is the value pick of the lineup — $100 cheaper with the same Focus Pro 30K sensor and a slightly lighter shell. The only reasons to pay the premium are wireless freedom and battery life.</p>

      <p>Buy the Razer Viper V3 Pro instead if you want a symmetric shape or have smaller hands. The Viper V3 Pro uses the same sensor and wireless technology with identical weight and battery — only the shape is different. If you are unsure which Razer flagship to pick, the Viper is the safer all-rounder for most grip styles.</p>

      <p>Consider the Logitech G Pro X Superlight 2 if you want the cross-brand alternative. It is $10 more, 3 g lighter, and uses Logitech's HERO 2 sensor with marginally higher DPI. The choice between the two comes down to which shape fits your hand better. Pair the V3 Pro with a <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad</a> for consistent sensor tracking, and a <a href="/reviews/best-mechanical-keyboard-work/">mechanical keyboard</a> for a complete gaming setup.</p>

